# Pitfalls — API Response Shaping

Common mistakes developers make when shaping (or not shaping) API responses.

---

## 1. Returning the raw DB row directly

```js
// ❌ Exposing password_hash, internal_notes, stripe_customer_id to the client
return res.json(user);

// ✅ Shape it first
return res.json(shapeUser(user));
```

**Why it matters:** You've now leaked your DB schema AND sensitive data to every client that calls this endpoint. You'll have to change clients when you change your schema.

---

## 2. Shaping inconsistently across endpoints

```js
// ❌ GET /users returns { avatarUrl }
// ❌ GET /users/:id returns { avatar_url }
// ❌ GET /me returns { profilePicture }
```

Three endpoints, three different field names for the same thing. The client now needs to handle all three cases.

**Fix:** Create a single `shapeUser()` function and use it everywhere. One shape, one contract.

---

## 3. Shaping in the wrong layer

```js
// ❌ Shaping inside a SQL query — tightly coupled
const user = await db.query(`
  SELECT id, full_name AS "fullName", avatar_url AS "avatarUrl" FROM users
`);

// ❌ Shaping on the frontend — sensitive data already sent over the wire
const safeUser = { id: user.id, name: user.name }; // strip in the client

// ✅ Shape in the API layer (route handler or controller)
const user = await db.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1', [id]);
return res.json(shapeUser(user.rows[0]));
```

Shaping in SQL makes your queries fragile. Shaping on the frontend means you've already exposed the raw data.

---

## 4. Forgetting to shape nested/joined data

```js
// ❌ Author is raw DB data nested inside the post
return res.json({
  id: post.id,
  title: post.title,
  author: {
    id: post.author_id,
    name: post.author_name,
    password_hash: post.author_password_hash, // 💀
  },
});

// ✅ Shape each nested resource
return res.json(shapePost(post)); // shapePost calls shapeAuthor internally
```

---

## 5. Treating computed fields as DB responsibilities

```js
// ❌ Storing `initials`, `full_name`, `member_since_year` as columns
// — means you sync them on every update, they can drift

// ✅ Compute at the API shaping layer — always accurate
function shapeUser(user) {
  return {
    ...
    initials: user.name.split(' ').map(n => n[0]).join('').toUpperCase(),
    memberSince: new Date(user.created_at).getFullYear(),
  };
}
```

---

## 6. No response envelope for lists

```js
// ❌ Just returning an array
return res.json(users.map(shapeUser));

// Client has no idea how many total records exist.
// They can't paginate. They can't show "Page 3 of 12".

// ✅ Wrap in an envelope
return res.json(paginatedResponse(users.map(shapeUser), total, page, pageSize));
```

---

## 7. Changing field names without versioning

Your API is a public contract. If your frontend or mobile app expects `avatarUrl` and you rename it to `profileImage` in the shaper, the client breaks.

**Fix:** Version your API (`/api/v1/`, `/api/v2/`) or maintain backwards compatibility by keeping old field names until all clients migrate.

---

## 8. Shaping at the ORM model level only

ORMs like Prisma let you `select` specific fields. That's great for query efficiency, but it's not enough — it doesn't rename fields, add computed values, or enforce role-based visibility.

```js
// ✅ Use Prisma select for DB efficiency
const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({
  where: { id },
  select: { id: true, name: true, email: true, avatar_url: true, created_at: true },
});

// ✅ Then still run it through your shaper
return res.json(shapeUser(user));
```

Think of the Prisma `select` as a first-pass filter. The shaper does the final transform.

---

## 9. Over-shaping: creating too many shaper variants

```js
// ❌ Too many bespoke shapers
shapeUserForDashboard()
shapeUserForProfile()
shapeUserForSearch()
shapeUserForEmails()
shapeUserForMobileApp()
```

If you end up with ten shaper variants for the same resource, it's a sign that your base shaper is too rigid. Use a role/context argument instead, or compose from a base shaper.

---

## Summary

| Pitfall | Quick Fix |
|---|---|
| Raw DB row returned | Always call `shapeX()` before `res.json()` |
| Inconsistent field names | One shaper per resource, used everywhere |
| Shaping in SQL / on client | Shape in the API layer only |
| Forgetting nested data | Each nested resource gets its own shaper |
| Arrays with no envelope | Use `paginatedResponse()` wrapper |
| Rename fields without care | Version your API or maintain backwards compat |
| Skipping shaper after Prisma select | Prisma select ≠ response shaping |